International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Tue 14 Sep 2010 4:16 PM
From: From: Ramon Noseda <rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar> [edited]


Rural outbreak of anthrax
-------------------------
Anthrax has been confirmed on a cattle estancia [ranch] some 20 km
[12 mi] from Ayacucho in the province of Buenos Aires. The herd is
made up of 300 red and black Aberdeen Angus heifers which had been
vaccinated with Sterne in April 2010. There is a prior history of
anthrax. The affected animal suddenly died and there was blood from
her various natural openings (nose, mouth, vagina, etc). The
estancia's veterinarian extracted a metacarpal bone -- standard
Argentine procedure -- and referred it to the laboratory for
diagnosis. [_Bacillus anthracis_] was confirmed by culture.

There are no human infections. The carcass was covered with lime and
a thick plastic tarpaulin in the standard "tapado controlado"
procedure [controlled covered technique].

--
Dr Ramon Noseda
Laboratorio Azul Diagnostico SA
Av 25 de Mayo 479
(B7300FXE) Azul - Pcia Bs As
Argentina
<rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar>
<http://www.laboratorioazul.com.ar>

[The problem of animals unprotected by a prior vaccination is chronic
in this part of Argentina. The cause evades clarification. The
vaccine strain of Sterne is standard and has the necessary numbers of
pag and lef genes. These are beef herds and so we do not have the
problem seen elsewhere with dairy cows being simultaneously treated
for mastitis with antibiotics. Any suggestions would be welcome.

For maps of Argentina, go to
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/argentina_rel96.jpg>,
<http://www.embassyworld.com/maps/Maps_Of_Argentina/index.php>, and
<http://healthmap.org/r/07Gz>. - Mod.MHJ]
